{"id":"2106.04040","submitter":"Leonardo Dos Anjos Cunha","authors":"Leonardo A. Cunha, Joonho Lee, Diptarka Hait, C. William McCurdy and\n  Martin Head-Gordon","title":"Exploring Spin Symmetry-Breaking Effects for Static Field Ionization of\n  Atoms: Is There an Analog to the Coulson-Fischer Point in Bond Dissociation?","comments":null,"journal-ref":"J. Chem. Phys. 155, 014309 (2021)","doi":"10.1063/5.0054387","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph physics.atm-clus","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  L\\\"owdin's symmetry dilemma is an ubiquitous issue in approximate quantum\nchemistry. In the context of Hartree-Fock (HF) theory, the use of Slater\ndeterminants with some imposed constraints to preserve symmetries of the exact\nproblem may lead to physically unreasonable potential energy surfaces. On the\nother hand, lifting these constraints leads to the so-called broken symmetry\nsolutions that usually provide better energetics, at the cost of losing\ninformation about good quantum numbers that describe the state of the system.\nThis behavior has been previously extensively studied in the context of bond\ndissociation. This paper studies the behavior of different classes of\nHartree-Fock spin polarized solutions (restricted, unrestricted, generalized)\nin the context of ionization by strong static electric fields. We find that,\nfor simple two-electron systems, UHF is able to provide a qualitatively good\ndescription of states involved during the ionization process (neutral,\nsingly-ionized and doubly ionized states), whereas RHF fails to describe the\nsingly ionized state. For more complex systems, even though UHF is able to\ncapture some of the expected characteristics of the ionized states, it is\nconstrained to a single $M_s$ (diabatic) manifold in the energy surface as a\nfunction of field intensity. In this case a better qualitative picture can be\npainted by GHF as it is able to explore different spin manifolds and follow the\nlowest solution due to lack of collinearity constraints on the spin\nquantization axis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 8 Jun 2021 01:22:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-22"}
